## purpose
Defines the canonical architectural role of skill in CivilizationOS.

## design_intent
Skill is the bounded capability structure
through which an actor's applicable ability,
proficiency,
specialization,
and limitations
become meaningful.

Skill is not identical to job.
Job is a role-bearing institutional function,
while skill is the capability that may support one or more jobs,
activities,
or quests.

## architectural_position
Skill sits between:
- actor capability
- education/training influence
- job eligibility
- work execution
- quest progression
- evaluation and review

## required_behavior
- skill identity must remain explicit
- skill level or proficiency basis must remain explicit
- skill applicability scope must remain explicit
- current and historical skill states must remain distinguishable
- skill must not imply unlimited authority

## canonical_rules
- skill presence does not imply job assignment
- skill evaluation must not overwrite actor identity truth
- historical skill progression must remain queryable
- ambiguous skill applicability fails closed

## state_model
The skill domain distinguishes:
- declared skill
- trained skill
- active/applicable skill
- restricted skill
- deprecated skill
- historical skill

## actor_boundary
- skill holder
- evaluator
- operator
- reviewer
- adapter

## decision_matrix
- if skill identity is unclear, stop skill-sensitive paths
- if applicability scope is unclear, fail closed
- if evaluation basis is unclear, route to review
- if skill becomes historical, preserve progression trace

## review_checklist
- skill identity is explicit
- proficiency basis is explicit
- applicability scope is explicit
- historical distinction is explicit
